  "text": "Information can be valuable when it facilitates improved decision-making in the face of temporal uncertainty, such as that associated with rainfall fluctuations. Since climate variability can result in massive financial and human losses due to droughts, floods and costly risk mitigation strategies, it may pay to have timely, reliable climate forecasts to help people choose optimal state-contingent livelihood strategies, both to avoid disaster and to capitalize on temporary, favorable states of nature. Recognizing the value seasonal climate forecasts could have to subsistence farmers and pastoralists 4 living in the arid and semi-arid lands (ASAL) of Sub-Saharan Africa (SSA) and elsewhere, several development agencies have directed attention and funding to establishing Famine Early Warning Systems (FEWS) over the past two decades [CITATION_1] [CITATION_2] . More recently, a big push has been made to augment FEWS with computer models of coupled atmospheric-oceanic circulation patterns that translate data on wind speed and direction, topography and sea surface temperatures into seasonal precipitation forecasts issued one to six months ahead.",
